english:
  title: Edict Refusing Choi Jeong-hwa's Declining of the Position of Vice Minister of the Secretariat
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    ...The office of Vice Minister stands second only to the Prime Minister, known as the Minister of Military Affairs. It is where the imperial command is received and executed, where all matters of state and military are decided. Surely we must select the most worthy for such a post.

    You have long been descended from a noble house and have risen through the ranks of our court. Measured in speech and calm in demeanor, you have never been rash. Diligent in your duties, you have always upheld propriety. From governing the Southern Province, you were called to serve in the Ministry of Justice; from overseeing the Palace Relatives Bureau, you were transferred to the Ministry of Works. In every position you have conducted yourself with grace and competence—who would dare criticize you?

    Moreover, your maternal grandfather, in serving our late father the King, took pity on soldiers marching into distant campaigns, exposed to wind and rain in mountain wilds. Wherever troops were encamped, he established lodgings for their rest. This is a kindness that all the soldiers of the Three Han still praise to this day. Your own merits are considerable, and you inherit the accumulated virtue of your grandfather's benevolence. Long have you deserved our highest favor and trust.

    Now we entrust you with this position of Vice Minister of the Secretariat, a duty that should have come to you sooner. Why then do you hesitate and decline?...
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The ''Three Han'' (三韓) refers to the three ancient Korean kingdoms: Goguryeo, Baekje, and Silla, though here it likely refers to the unified Korean kingdom and its people.'
  - key: ''
    value: This is a royal edict (교서) refusing a subject's request to decline a court appointment, a rhetorical form that both flatters the appointee and subtly pressures him to accept the honor.
  - key: ''
    value: The progression through various ministries—Justice, Palace Relatives, and Works—demonstrates a careful career advancement through different branches of government.
